        </div><div class="card-headline"><h3 class="tnt-headline ">
        
             <a href="/news/local/virginia-may-take-1-billion-annual-revenue-hit-in-new-budget-because-of-coronavirus/article_49e31f12-5c75-52b1-b375-c58770cf1743.html" class="tnt-asset-link">
        

        
            Virginia may take $1 billion annual revenue hit in new budget because of coronavirus</a></h3></div><div class="card-meta">
            <ul class="list-inline">
                        <li class="card-byline text-muted"><span  class="tnt-byline">By MICHAEL MARTZ
Richmond Times-Dispatch
</span></li><li class="card-date">
        <time datetime="2020-03-24T08:00:00-04:00" class="tnt-date asset-date text-muted">Mar 24, 2020</time></li><li class="card-comment-count"><a href="/news/local/virginia-may-take-1-billion-annual-revenue-hit-in-new-budget-because-of-coronavirus/article_49e31f12-5c75-52b1-b375-c58770cf1743.html#comments" class="cm" title="0 comments"><span class="fas tnt-comments"></span> <span class="count">0</span></a></li></ul>
        </div>
                    
                    
                    
                    
                        
                        
                            <div class="card-lead">
                                <p class="tnt-summary"><p>Virginia’s top finance official says the state is likely to lose $1 billion in revenue in each year of the pending two-year budget — and that’s the best scenario, assuming significant aid from the federal government for workers and business owners who have lost their livelihoods because of the coronavirus pandemic.</p></p>
                            </div>
                        
                    
                    
                    
                    
                    
                </div>
            </div>
