        </div><div class="card-headline"><h3 class="tnt-headline ">
        
             <a href="/news/local/local-courts-to-remain-open-limit-hearings/article_fd33ddf7-aa41-5669-894f-c48d21e5e81c.html" class="tnt-asset-link">
        

        
            Local courts to remain open, limit hearings</a></h3></div><div class="card-meta">
            <ul class="list-inline">
                        <li class="card-byline text-muted"><span id="author-409fd64e-f003-11e7-a5ae-3b6be71044b5-asset-fd33ddf7-aa41-5669-894f-c48d21e5e81c" class="tnt-byline asset-byline"  >By TYLER HAMMEL
thammel@dailyprogress.com </p><p>(434) 978-7268

</span>
                </li><li class="card-date">
        <time datetime="2020-03-17T15:42:00-04:00" class="tnt-date asset-date text-muted">Mar 17, 2020</time></li><li class="card-comment-count"><a href="/news/local/local-courts-to-remain-open-limit-hearings/article_fd33ddf7-aa41-5669-894f-c48d21e5e81c.html#comments" class="cm" title="0 comments"><span class="fas tnt-comments"></span> <span class="count">0</span></a></li></ul>
        </div>
                    
                    
                    
                    
                        
                        
                            <div class="card-lead">
                                <p class="tnt-summary"><p>The decision to remain open follows an order Monday from Donald Lemons, Chief Justice of the Virginia Supreme Court, that said that non-essential, non-emergency court proceedings in all circuit and district courts in Virginia should be suspended until April 6.</p></p>
                            </div>
                        
                    
                    
                    
                    
                    
                </div>
